    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage keeps your monthly payment the same for the entire loan term, while an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) has a fixed rate for an initial period before it can change based on market conditions. If you are looking at a 5-year window, an ARM will typically stay fixed for that duration, but the moment that 5-year period ends, your payment could spike if interest rates have risen significantly. For example, if rates jump by 2% after the initial term, your monthly payment could increase by roughly 200% of the original rate's value, depending on your loan balance. You would need to budget for these potential fluctuations, as a sudden increase could make your home unaffordable if you don't have a financial cushion.",
